Adverse health effects of noise and air pollution are well documented.
 Chronic traffic noise exposure in urban environments can cause severe sleep
 disturbance, hearing impairment, tinnitus, and raised stress levels, leading
 to high blood pressure, coronary heart disease, stroke, and possibly immune
 system and birth defects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "passchier-vermeer:2000"

\end_inset

.
 The various adverse health effects of air pollution are summarised in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:air-poll-Health-effects"

\end_inset

.
 Certain groups are particularly susceptible to air pollution, including
 those with respiratory or cardiac diseases or asthma, infants, children
 and the elderly, and those with low socio-economic status (SES), low levels
 of education, poor nutrition and poor general health 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "utell:2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "welsch:2006"

\end_inset

, this link does not require that individuals are conscious of the causal
 relationship between an environmental problem and their own happiness.
 However, awareness of a local environmental problem, and of its negative
 effects on human and ecosystem health, could also act to reduce happiness
 levels directly and independently.
 There is evidence that individuals' perceptions of air pollution are positively
 correlated with objective pollution measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "day:2007"

\end_inset

.
 Individuals are generally aware of the sources of pollution (principally,
 main roads), of its fluctuation according to weather conditions, and of
 the negative health effects with which it is associated, especially for
 children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bickerstaff:2001"

\end_inset

.
 This makes individuals' perceptions of air pollution an additional route
 by which the pollution may influence their happiness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Associated benefits of natural environments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, natural environments might increase happiness by facilitating and
 encouraging --- for practical, cultural and/or psychological reasons ---
 behaviours that are physically and mentally beneficial, including physical
 exercise, recreation and social interaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "barton:2010a,morris:2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Evidence
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:eq-swb-evidence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers in urban planning, epidemiology and psychology have pursued
 observational and experimental evidence on links between physical or mental
 wellbeing and EQ.
 Economists have sought observational evidence of links between happiness
 and EQ, generally using these to derive monetary valuations of EQ parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Studies outside economics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Studies-outside-economics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observational studies have compared individuals' health and wellbeing reports
 or medical records with the proximity of their homes to natural environments,
 or with alternative indicators of local environmental quality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "kaplan:2001,takano:2002,vries:2003,grahn:2003,maas:2006,nielsen:2007,bjork:2008a,maas:2009"

\end_inset

.
 On occasion they have also related averaged wellbeing measures to aggregate
 environmental characteristics between geographical regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "mitchell:2007"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental and quasi-experimental studies have investigated physiological
 and psychological effects of exposure to images of different environment
 types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "berto:2005,white:2010,ryan:2010"

\end_inset

 or to short-term interventions bringing subjects into contact with nature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "hartig:2003,pretty:2007,berman:2008,barton:2010,ryan:2010,martens:2011"

\end_inset

.
 They have also related health and wellbeing indicators to views of nature
 in settings where individuals' accommodation is assigned exogenously: public
 housing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kuo:2001a"

\end_inset

, prisons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moore:1981"

\end_inset

, and hospitals (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "ulrich:1984"

\end_inset

's much-cited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "ulrich:1984"

\end_inset

 paper in 
\emph on
Science
\emph default
, 'View through a window may influence recovery from surgery').
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most studies report beneficial impacts of natural environments on health
 or wellbeing, but they have some common weaknesses.
 Observational studies measure domestic proximity to natural environments
 but rarely look at actual experiences of such environments (which may not
 occur near home, and may occur elsewhere); cannot provide data on the moment-by
-moment hedonic or affective element of wellbeing; and are reliant on retrospect
ive assessments that are subject to substantial recall bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "robinson:2002"

\end_inset

.
 Experimental studies are stronger in these respects but --- with the possible
 exception of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "kuo:2001a"

\end_inset

's --- by their nature tell us a limited amount about peoples' real experiences
 of natural environments in their everyday lives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Studies in conventional economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In economics, relationships between location and quality of life have long
 been a subject of interest in the hedonic pricing literature, in which
 environmental and urban amenities have been used to account for regional
 wage and rent differentials and construct 'objective' quality of life indices
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

.
 Hedonic valuation has been used to investigate the impacts of various EQ
 parameters, including road noise, air quality, water quality, forests,
 wetlands, view of nature, urban trees and open spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smith:2010"

\end_inset

 finds that each hectare of parkland within 1km increases London house prices
 by 0.08%, while a large park within 600 metres adds 2 -- 3% to a house's
 value, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibbons:2011a"

\end_inset

 find that local green space, water, woodland and farmland attract a considerabl
e house price premium in England, while increasing distance to natural amenities
 such as rivers and National Parks is associated with a fall in house prices.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibbons:2011a"

\end_inset

 also provide a more complete survey of studies of this type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedonic pricing studies have most commonly used only distances as indicators
 of EQ characteristics, although the two studies cited exploit improved
 GIS capabilities to also consider the local quantities of certain amenities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Studies in happiness economics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:eq-swb-economic-studies"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Environmental-and-ecological"

\end_inset

, environmental economists have more recently begun to use SWB data to quantify
 the impacts of EQ characteristics --- either directly, in terms of their
 effects on SWB, or in monetary terms.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 398"
key "welsch:2009"

\end_inset

 give a synopsis of selected studies valuing EQ through SWB.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Air quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Welsch (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2002"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2003"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2006"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

), examining average SWB in relation to average (objective) air pollution
 values at country level, finds significant negative associations in each
 case.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "menz:2010"

\end_inset

, using data across 25 countries, find that higher PM10 concentrations are
 associated with reduced SWB and that the magnitude of this effect is ---
 like the health impairments associated with air pollution --- U-shaped
 in age.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rehdanz:2007"

\end_inset

 find that 
\emph on
perceived
\emph default
 levels of air pollution are negatively related to SWB scores in Germany.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

, working with individual-level data on air pollution and other EQ parameters
 in Ireland, also find negative associations between air pollution and SWB,
 as do 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mackerron:2008"

\end_inset

, using high-resolution air pollution data for London, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "levinson:2009"

\end_inset

, who makes use of temporal variations in air pollution levels in US counties,
 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

, who uses the installation of scrubbers at a power plant in Germany as
 a natural experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Climate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "frijters:1998"

\end_inset

 find that individual-level SWB in Russia is positively associated with
 hours of sunshine, days of rain, and interactions of average temperature
 with precipitation and temperature with windspeed in January, and negatively
 related to quantity of rainfall, January windspeed, and interactions of
 average humidity with temperature and rural location with precipitation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rehdanz:2005"

\end_inset

, looking at climate parameters at country level across 67 countries, find
 that higher mean SWB is associated with higher mean temperature during
 cold months and lower mean temperature during hot months.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "maddison:2010a"

\end_inset

, using data from 87 countries, conclude that deviations from an ideal temperatu
re of 18.3°C significantly reduce life satisfaction.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 find higher individual SWB in Ireland to be related positively to annual
 hours of sunshine and millimetres of rainfall, and negatively to wind speeds.
 Using the same data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 find a positive association in Ireland between SWB and average temperatures
 in both January and June
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 do not find a significant temperature effect, but 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 include fewer other climate parameters in their model, so the difference
 in findings might be a result of omitted variables or of multicolinearity
 in the explanatory variables.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand Citet
key "praag:2005"

\end_inset

, investigating aircraft noise around Amsterdam Schiphol airport, find that
 individuals' experienced noise nuisance is negatively related to SWB, although
 direct noise measures are not significant.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "weinhold:2008"

\end_inset

 finds 
\emph on
perceived
\emph default
 noise pollution levels a strongly negative predictor of SWB in individual-level
 data across Europe.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Waste sites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

 find that very close residential proximity to landfill sites (being within
 the same electoral district) has a negative SWB association, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 reach the same conclusion regarding the per capita number of landfill sites
 by local authority area.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 do not find a significant effect of landfill sites within 5km, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

 detect no impact of proximity to hazardous waste facilities, however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Water quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "israel:2003"

\end_inset

 report that individuals' life satisfaction is negatively associated with
 country-level per capita emissions of organic water pollutants.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 detect no significant effect of being situated within 5km of a 'severely
 polluted' river.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Coastline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 find that close proximity to coastline (within 2km or in the same local
 authority area respectively) has a positive association with SWB, but 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 find no significant effect of coastline within 5km.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Biodiversity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rehdanz:2007a"

\end_inset

 runs spatial regression models with country-level data on simple counts
 of bird and mammal species, and the proportions of species that are threatened,
 and suggests that greater numbers of species, and lower proportions of
 bird species threatened, are associated with higher SWB.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Natural capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vemuri:2006"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "engelbrecht:2009"

\end_inset

 report positive relationships between indicators of wellbeing and generalised
 'natural capital' at country level.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "vemuri:2006"

\end_inset

 measure natural capital as the 'ecosystem services product' based on land
 cover types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sutton:2002"

\end_inset

, which can arguably be considered EQ-related.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "engelbrecht:2009"

\end_inset

's natural capital figures do not appear to be appropriate EQ measures,
 however, since reserves of resources such as metal ores, oil and coal feature
 heavily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Country-level studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several studies compare mean SWB and mean EQ values at the whole-country
 level (all Welsch's air pollution papers cited above; 
