\begin_layout Standard
Having reflected on previous research both in happiness economics in general
 and into the relationship of happiness to EQ, the new research described
 in the remainder of this thesis has two strands.
 Both strands involve substantial new primary data collection.
 Both seek to test the hypothesis that EQ characteristics are significantly
 related to individuals' SWB, and to measure the extent of these relationships,
 in some cases in monetary terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first strand builds directly on previous EQ research in happiness economics,
 linking recalled happiness assessments to respondents' usual environments,
 and improving on this in a number of areas.
 The second strand updates the ESM protocol to facilitate very large sample
 sizes, and to incorporate satellite positioning (GPS) location data that
 can be used within a GIS to estimate objective indicators of EQ.
 The first strand is largely evolutionary, while the second is a little
 more revolutionary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time is not the researcher's friend.
 The second strand is reliant on consumer technology that became available
 only after the research had started, and has potential for exploitation
 enormously beyond what has been possible within the constraints of the
 doctorate.
 Meanwhile the first strand, having been conceived of several years ago,
 has in certain respects been overtaken by developments elsewhere.
 Nevertheless, both strands still offer some significant advances on earlier
 research in this field.
\end_layout

